{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5d6f4c99-78a1-43a3-8c6d-ccb4543f4b78","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n## 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the default **test ID generation strategy** from `FullyQualified` to `DisplayName`. Since Azure DevOps tracks tests by their stable ID, all tests appear as new.\n\n**Fix** — add this to your `.runsettings` or project:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>FullyQualified</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it's no longer tied to a specific test method. Accessing `TestName` now throws `InvalidOperationException`. In v3 it returned the first test's name (which was unreliable anyway).\n\nYour `SetupTests.cs` (line 13) hits this directly:\n\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // throws in v4\n```\n\nRemove or guard that access — class-level setup shouldn't depend on a test name.\n\n## Other v4 breaking changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | Implicit conversions (e.g., `int` → `long`) are stricter; mismatches may fail at runtime |\n| **Parallel execution** | Now enabled by default; tests sharing static state may see race conditions |\n| **`[DeploymentItem]`** | Behavior tightened; relative paths resolve differently |\n| **`Assert.ThrowsException`** | No longer catches derived exception types by default — must be exact match |\n| **Timeout** | `[Timeout]` now uses `CancellationToken` cooperative cancellation instead of `Thread.Abort` |\n\nReview the [MSTest v4 migration guide](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/core/testing/mstest-analyzers/mstest-migration) for the full list. The parallelism change tends to be the most disruptive if tests weren't already isolated.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d4db37d4-d8cd-4ad5-a9f1-a71fa849c6c9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide answers based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 changes:\n\n1. **Test ID changes (lost history in Azure DevOps)**: MSTest v4 changed the default test ID generation strategy. In v3, the default was `TestIdGenerationStrategy.FullyQualified`, but in v4 it changed to `TestIdGenerationStrategy.DisplayName`. This means test IDs are different, causing Azure DevOps to treat them as new tests with no history.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]**: In MSTest v4, `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is no longer associated with a specific test method (since class initialization runs once before all tests in the class). Accessing `TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException`. In v3, it would return the name of the first test to run, which was essentially a bug/undefined behavior.\n\n\n3. There are several other breaking changes worth noting beyond these two main ones.","outputTokens":780,"requestId":"481E:16A66F:6675307:6EE00F9:69FC0162"},"id":"21398e93-fd11-4545-920f-2b3620cb3f66","timestamp":"2026-05-07T03:05:23.688Z","parentId":"e915f54b-bb84-4e73-8e4f-f8d3def26a5b"}
